The dataset contains 10019 records about YouTube cat-related videos. We use English and Russian search queries to get data in order to cover as much audience as we can. Some Japanese and Korean videos appear also, it's have been discovered by tags or titles. For example English titles with Korean tags. But it was quite a few of them, so no great influence prognosis.

  1. Id - technical identifier;
  2. Video ID - unique Youtube identifier of video;
  3. Title;
  4. Video tags;
  5. Date of publishing;
  6. Duration in seconds;
  7. View count of particular video;
  8. Likes count;
  9. Dislikes count;
  10. 'Add to Favourite' count;
  11. Comments count;
  12. Category - technical data about video category. Have been used in data scrapping;
  13. Channel Id - unique Youtube identifier of channel;
  14. Channel country;
  15. View count of channel;
  16. Comments count of channel;
  17. Subscribers count of channel;
  18. Videos count of channel.

We aim to prognose the View count of a particular video against other data. Clearly understood that technical identifiers like Video ID or Channel ID have no influence on View count, so we need to choose data correctly. A closer look at the dataset shows that 'Add to Favourite' count and Channel comments count are always 0, so we don't need them. Channel category fixed also. It would be nice to have the Channel country in the dataset, but values are very dense and we might have low influence 'cause of the data lack.

Let's do some data preparation: separate data that we need only, normalize numeric values in the range [0, 1], transform date values to timestamp and remove empty values of Video tags.

Let's check if numeric data in the dataset conform to normal distribution. We'll use the following criteria for each numeric data column:

  1. D'Agostino criteria;
  2. Jarque-Bera criteria;
  3. Kolmogorov-Smirnov criteria;
  4. Wilcox criteria.
In [3]:
alpha = 1e-3

from scipy.stats import normaltest
from scipy.stats import jarque_bera
from scipy.stats import kstest
from scipy.stats import wilcoxon

normal_distr_data = data.select_dtypes(include=numerics)

for column in normal_distr_data:
    stat, p = normaltest(normal_distr_data[column])
    print('D\'Agostino hypothesis for {} {}'.format(column, 'approved' if p < alpha else 'rejected'))
    stat, p = jarque_bera(normal_distr_data[column])
    print('Jarque-Bera hypothesis for {} {}'.format(column, 'approved' if p < alpha else 'rejected'))
    stat, p = kstest(normal_distr_data[column], 'norm')
    print('Kolmogorov-Smirnov hypothesis for {} {}'.format(column, 'approved' if p < alpha else 'rejected'))
    stat, p = wilcoxon(normal_distr_data[column])
    print('Wilcoxon hypothesis for {} {}'.format(column, 'approved' if p < alpha else 'rejected'))

Now we need to classify text data. Using K-means's intertia parameter determine optimal cluster quantity for Titles and Viedeo tags. Then TF IDF separates Titles and Video tags to determine number of clusters and replaces label with mean View count by cluster.

In [4]:
import nltk
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

titles = data['title']

stopwords_list = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english') + nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('russian') + ['vs']
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words=stopwords_list)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(titles)
inertia = []
for k in range(1, 15):
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='k-means++', max_iter=100, n_init=1, random_state=42)
    model.fit(X)
    inertia.append(model.inertia_)
In [5]:
plt.plot(inertia, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Optimal clusters quantity')
plt.show()
In [6]:
true_k = 6
model = KMeans(n_clusters=true_k, init='k-means++', max_iter=100, n_init=1, random_state=42)
model.fit(X)
title_clusters = []
for title in titles:
    val = model.predict(vectorizer.transform([title]))[0]
    if val:
        title_clusters.append(val)
    else:
        title_clusters.append(0)
        
title_df = pandas.DataFrame({'title_cluster': title_clusters})

data = data.join(title_df)

Video duration has no correlation to any parameter at all, so it might be excluded from the model. High correlation to View count has the following parameters:

  1. Likes count;
  2. Dislikes count;
  3. Comments count;
  4. Channel subscribers count.

But Dislikes count and Comments count correlate to Likes count also. Take as base parameter Likes count calculate Dislikes count and Comments count using Linear regression. Then use only the residual values in the model.

Do the same with Channel subscribers count and Channel view count.

As far as we get rid of correlation we're ready to build the first model for prediction. Build a few models to compare its results. As criteria take RMSE.

For the first step, we'll build naive NN: two layers contain one neuron each. Just for fun :) Model's hyperparameters obtained experimentally.

In [28]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data[['likeCount', 'dislikeCount', 'commentCount', 'channel_view_count',
                                                         'channel_videos_count', 'channel_subscribers_count']].values, 
                                                    data[['viewCount']].values,
                                                    test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

X_train = X_train.reshape((X_train.shape[0], 1, X_train.shape[1]))
y_train = y_train.reshape((y_train.shape[0], 1, y_train.shape[1]))
X_test = X_test.reshape((X_test.shape[0], 1, X_test.shape[1]))
y_test = y_test.reshape((y_test.shape[0], 1, y_test.shape[1]))
In [29]:
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense
from numpy.random import seed
import keras.losses as loss

seed(42)

def rmse(y_test, y_pred):
    return loss.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred) ** 0.5

batch_size = 100
epoch = 20

n_model = Sequential()
n_model.add(Dense(1, activation='relu'))
n_model.add(Dense(1, activation='tanh'))
n_model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='adam', metrics=[rmse])
history = n_model.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=batch_size, epochs=epoch, validation_data=(X_test, y_test),
                      verbose=0)
score = n_model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size)
print('{:4e}'.format(score[1]))

In [32]:
def RMSE(y_test, y_pred):
    return (sum((y_test - y_pred) ** 2) / len(y_test)) ** 0.5

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

for i in range(1, 5):
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=i, include_bias=False)
    X_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(X_train)
    lin_reg = LinearRegression()
    lin_reg.fit(X_poly, y_train)
    print(i, '{:4e}'.format(RMSE(y_test, lin_reg.predict(poly_features.fit_transform(X_test)))[0]))

from talos import Scan
from keras.activations import *
from keras.optimizers import Adam
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense

from keras.layers import Dropout

def opt_model_f(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, params):
    opt_model = Sequential()
    opt_model.add(Dense(params['first_layer'], activation=params['first_layer_activation']))
    opt_model.add(Dropout(params['dropout']))
    opt_model.add(Dense(1, activation=params['last_layer_activation']))
    opt_model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer=Adam(lr=params['lr']), metrics=[rmse])
    history = opt_model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), batch_size=params['batch_size'],
                            epochs=params['epoch'], verbose=0)
    return history, opt_model

p = {
    'first_layer': [1, 2, 10, 50],
    'first_layer_activation': [elu, relu, selu],

    'epoch': [20, 50, 100, 200],

from keras.optimizers import Adam
seed(42)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    data[['likeCount', 'dislikeCount', 'commentCount', 'channel_view_count',
          'channel_videos_count', 'channel_subscribers_count']].values,
    data[['viewCount']].values,
    test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

X_train = X_train.reshape((X_train.shape[0], 1, X_train.shape[1]))
y_train = y_train.reshape((y_train.shape[0], 1, y_train.shape[1]))
X_test = X_test.reshape((X_test.shape[0], 1, X_test.shape[1]))
y_test = y_test.reshape((y_test.shape[0], 1, y_test.shape[1]))

new_model = Sequential()
new_model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
new_model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
new_model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer=Adam(lr=0.05), metrics=[rmse])
history = new_model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), batch_size=50, epochs=100, verbose=0)
score = new_model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, batch_size=50)
print('{:4e}'.format(score[1]))

Use an optimized model for View count prediction. For example, we have a YouTube channel with cat videos. We post new ones and ask subscribers about 10000 likes :) For example, take:

  1. Likes count - 8675 / 1202126 = 0.00721638;
  2. Diskiles count - 547 / 88114 = 0.00620787;
  3. Comments count - 165 / 120440 = 0.00137;
  4. Channel view count - 154862 / 14251756132 = 0.00001087;
  5. Channel videos count - 57 / 138607 = 0.00041123;
  6. Channel subscribers count - 12547 / 22093838 = 0.0005679.
